06571nam a22011535i 9780691208121DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020947160  a97806912081217 a10.1515/97806912081212doi  a(DE-B1597)567579  a(OCoLC)1228505050  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0360602bisacsh1 aHull, Katy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Machine Has a Soul :bAmerican Sympathy with Italian Fascism /cKaty Hull. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b15 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerica in the World ;v4100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: The Machine with a Soul -- t1. The Good Adventure: Fascist Squads in a War-Weary World -- t2 Mystic in a Morning Coat: Americans' Mussolini in the 1920s -- t3 The Dream Machine: The Fascist State in an Era of Democratic Disillusionment -- t4 Man as the Measure of All Things: Sympathizing with Fascism in the Early Depression Years -- t5 The Garden of Fascism: Beauty, Transcendence, and Peace in an Era of Uncertainty -- tConclusion: Searching for Soul under the Sign of the Machine -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA historical look at the American fascination with Italian fascism during the interwar periodIn the interwar years, the United States grappled with economic volatility and Americans expressed anxieties about a decline in moral values, the erosion of families and communities, and the decay of democracy. These issues prompted a profound ambivalence toward modernity, leading some individuals to turn to Italian fascism as a possible solution for the problems facing the country. The Machine Has a Soul delves into why Americans of all stripes sympathized with Italian fascism, and shows that fascism's appeal rested in the image of Mussolini's regime as "the machine which will run and has a soul"-a seemingly efficient and technologically advanced system that upheld tradition, religion, and family.Katy Hull focuses on four prominent American sympathizers: Richard Washburn Child, a conservative diplomat and Republican operative; Anne O'Hare McCormick, a distinguished New York Times journalist; Generoso Pope, an Italian-American publisher and Democratic political broker; and Herbert Wallace Schneider, a Columbia University professor of moral philosophy. In fascism's violent squads they saw youthful glamour and impeccable manners, in the megalomaniacal Mussolini they perceived someone both current and old-fashioned, and in the corporate state they witnessed a politics that could revive addled minds. They argued that with the right course of action, the United States could use fascism to take the best from modernity while withstanding its harmful effects.Investigating the motivations of American fascist sympathizers, The Machine Has a Soul offers provocative lessons about authoritarianism's appeal during times of intense cultural, social, and economic strain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAnne O'Hare McCormick.  aColumbia University.  aFascist Modernities.  aFascist youth programs.  aGeneroso Pope.  aHerbert Schneider.  aItaly.  aJohn Diggins.  aJonah Goldberg.  aLiberal Fascism.  aModernism and Fascism.  aMussolini and Fascism.  aMussolini.  aNazi Germany.  aNew York Times.  aRichard Washburn Child.  aRoger Griffin.  aRuth Ben-Ghiat.  aVictorian ideals.  aauthoritarianism.  acorporate state.  afascist militarism.  afascist squadrism